caption: Figure 1: IGD curves averaged over 15 runs on the WFG5 problem instances for LORA-MOO with different parameter setups (shaded area is ± std of the mean).
description: This figure shows the impact of different parameter settings on the performance of the LORA-MOO algorithm.  Specifically, it illustrates the IGD (Inverted Generational Distance) values over 15 runs for the WFG5 problem (a widely used benchmark problem in multi-objective optimization) as the number of function evaluations increases.  The different lines represent variations in the minimal number of ordinal levels (no), the dominance coefficient (λ), and the ratio threshold of reference points (rp_ratio). The shaded area around each line represents the standard deviation of the mean IGD values, providing insight into the variability of the results. The figure is split into two subfigures: (a) shows results for a 10-variable, 3-objective problem; (b) displays the results for a 10-variable, 10-objective problem.

caption: Figure 1: IGD curves averaged over 15 runs on the WFG5 problem instances for LORA-MOO with different parameter setups (shaded area is ± std of the mean).
description: This figure displays the impact of four different parameters on the performance of the LORA-MOO algorithm.  The x-axis represents the number of function evaluations, while the y-axis shows the inverted generational distance (IGD) value, a measure of the algorithm's performance.  Lower IGD values indicate better performance. The figure shows that LORA-MOO's performance is impacted by the following parameters: minimal number of ordinal levels (n_o), dominance coefficient (λ), ratio threshold of reference points (rp_ratio), and clustering number for reproduction (n_c). Each line represents a different configuration of these parameters, and the shaded area represents the standard deviation. By comparing the various lines, we can observe which parameter settings lead to the best algorithm performance.

caption: Figure 3: Log(HVdiff) curves averaged over 30 runs on the NAS problem for the comparison algorithms.
description: This figure shows the optimization performance of three algorithms, KRVEA, KTA2, and LORA-MOO, on a real-world network architecture search (NAS) problem.  The y-axis represents the log of the difference between the maximum achievable hypervolume (HVmax) and the achieved hypervolume (HV) at each evaluation step, indicating the optimization progress towards the Pareto front.  The x-axis is the number of evaluations (function calls). The shaded areas represent the standard deviations across 30 independent runs of each algorithm. The figure shows that LORA-MOO achieves better hypervolume values than KTA2 and KRVEA as the number of evaluations increases, suggesting its superior performance in finding high-quality and diverse solutions in this complex, real-world optimization problem.

caption: Figure 4: Comparison of runtime averaged over 30 runs on benchmark problems D = 10 variables and M = 3, 4, 6, 8, and 10 objectives for the comparison algorithms. For each algorithm, its runtimes are normalized by the runtime it costed on 3-objective problems.
description: This figure shows the runtime comparison of different algorithms across varying numbers of objectives (M).  The runtime for each algorithm is normalized to its runtime when M=3, providing a relative comparison of efficiency as the number of objectives increases.  It highlights how the runtime changes for each algorithm as the problem complexity grows.

caption: Figure 5: Illustration of artificial clustering-based ordinal relations. Left: Non-dominated solutions without artificial ordinal relations. Right: Non-dominated solutions with artificial ordinal relations. Red solutions are new non-dominated solutions in L1, remaining blue solutions are moved to next ordinal level L2. Dash circles are clusters, green vectors are cluster centers.
description: This figure illustrates how artificial clustering-based ordinal relations are generated to improve the learning quality of ordinal relations for many objectives. The left panel shows non-dominated solutions without any artificial relations, while the right panel shows how the solutions are clustered and the new non-dominated solutions are selected, resulting in a more balanced distribution of solutions across ordinal levels.

caption: Figure 6: Diagram of a network architecture in NASbench201.
description: The figure shows a directed acyclic graph representing the architecture of a neural network in the NASbench201 dataset.  The graph has four nodes (0, 1, 2, 3) representing processing units, and six edges connecting the nodes. Each edge is labeled with a color, and a legend indicates that each color represents a different operation: zeroize, skip-connect, 1x1 convolution, 3x3 convolution, or 3x3 average pool. These operations are performed on the data as it passes through the edges of the graph. The architecture is defined by the specific operations assigned to each of the six edges. This figure is relevant to the problem of Network Architecture Search (NAS), and demonstrates how an architecture can be represented for optimization purposes in this particular benchmark.

caption: Figure 1: IGD curves averaged over 15 runs on the WFG5 problem instances for LORA-MOO with different parameter setups (shaded area is ± std of the mean).
description: This figure shows the inverted generational distance (IGD) curves for the LORA-MOO algorithm on the WFG5 problem.  Different parameter settings for LORA-MOO are tested: the minimal number of ordinal levels (n_o), the dominance coefficient (λ), and the ratio threshold of reference points (rp_ratio). Each line represents the average IGD over 15 runs for a specific parameter combination, with the shaded area representing the standard deviation. The x-axis represents the number of function evaluations, and the y-axis represents the IGD value.  The figure illustrates how different parameter choices affect the convergence speed and quality of the Pareto front approximation.

caption: Figure 1: IGD curves averaged over 15 runs on the WFG5 problem instances for LORA-MOO with different parameter setups (shaded area is ± std of the mean).
description: This figure shows the inverted generational distance (IGD) curves for the LORA-MOO algorithm on the WFG5 problem with different parameter settings.  The x-axis represents the number of function evaluations, and the y-axis represents the IGD value. Multiple curves are shown, each representing a different set of parameters used in the LORA-MOO algorithm. The shaded area around each curve represents the standard deviation of the IGD values across 15 independent runs. This visualization helps to understand how the performance of LORA-MOO is affected by different parameter choices and to identify the optimal parameter setting.

caption: Figure 7: Distribution of obtained non-dominated solutions on DTLZ2 with 10 variables and 3 objectives.
description: This figure shows the distribution of non-dominated solutions obtained by seven different algorithms (ParEGO, K-RVEA, KTA2, CSEA, REMO, OREA, and LORA-MOO) on the DTLZ2 problem with 10 decision variables and 3 objectives.  The green line represents the Pareto front (PF), providing a visual reference for evaluating the convergence and diversity of the solutions generated by each algorithm. The plots illustrate the spread and distribution of solutions in the objective space.  LORA-MOO's distribution is visually compared to the other methods, showing how it compares in terms of convergence towards the PF and diversity across the PF.

caption: Figure 1: IGD curves averaged over 15 runs on the WFG5 problem instances for LORA-MOO with different parameter setups (shaded area is ± std of the mean).
description: This figure shows the inverted generational distance (IGD) curves for the LORA-MOO algorithm on the WFG5 problem, which is a benchmark problem in many-objective optimization.  The algorithm was tested with different parameter settings to assess its robustness and sensitivity.  Each curve represents the average IGD over 15 independent runs. The shaded area represents the standard deviation of the mean IGD, illustrating the variability of the results. The figure highlights how different parameter choices affect the algorithm's convergence and the overall quality of the Pareto front approximation.
